
Employee classes ->i want to sort all employess based on employee number

for sorting we use comparator---->
compare(object obj1,object obj2)
return -ve if obj1 has to come before obj2
return +ve if obj1 has to come after obj2
return 0 if obj1 & obj2 are equal
based on ascending order
(e1,e2)->(e1<e2)?-1:(e1>e2):+1:0

sort based on alphabetical order
s1.compareTo(s2)


Anonymous inner class vs Lambda Expression

Anonymous inner class is more power full than lambda expression

Anonymous inner class
class without having names is called anonymous class
Tread t=new Thread()

Thread t=new Thread(){ //child class no name  it extends Thread class
....

};
we are writing a class that extends Thread class

Runnable r=new Runnable(){ //no name
}; implementing the interface

Wherever a one-time implementation was required,
we used Anonymous Inner Classes before Java 8;
Lambda Expressions replaced them for Functional Interfaces
to reduce code verbosity.

Why were Lambda Expressions introduced?

Because before Java 8, developers used Anonymous Inner Classes for
implementing Functional Interfaces, which required a lot of boilerplate code.
Lambda Expressions provide a concise way to represent the same functionality.


why Anonymous inner class is power full?

interface A{
  m1();
  m2();
}
A a=new A()
{
public void m1(){
}
public void m2(){
}
};

| Feature                       | Anonymous Inner Class | Lambda |
| ----------------------------- | --------------------- | ------ |
| Multiple abstract methods     | ✅ Yes                 | ❌ No   |
| Additional methods            | ✅ Yes                 | ❌ No   |
| Instance variables            | ✅ Yes                 | ❌ No   |
| Extend class                  | ✅ Yes                 | ❌ No   |
| Functional Interface required | ❌ No                  | ✅ Yes  |
| Less code                     | ❌ No                  | ✅ Yes  |


default methods:
without effecting implementation classes if we want
to add new method to the interface

** Default methods cannot provide implementations
for methods inherited from Object (hashCode(),
equals(), toString(), etc.) because class methods
from Object always take precedence, and allowing such
defaults would create ambiguity.**

is java support for multiple inheritance or not?
Diamond problem

class p1{
public void m1(){
System.out.println("p1.method")
}
}
class p2{
public void m1(){
System.out.println("p2.method")
}
}
class Test extends p1,p2{
public static void main(String args[]){
}
}

cant extend same methods compiler will get confused which
method should be compiled

java 8 feature ----->Multiple inheritance (important)
-------------------------------------------------------
in implementation class we can override use super keyword

why static method came?
utility methods :add(),sub(),product()

before jav 8 these utility methods are declared inside in  the class


general utility methods no need to go for class instead go for interface